  <note>
    <title>[CPS+fungus]</title>
    <created>20180126T063111Z</created>
    <updated>20230825T081206Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>chronic sinusitis with chronic noninvasive fungal ball.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows prominent fungal balls composed of fungal</div><div>element with sepated hyphae and yeast forms. No invasion</div><div>into mucosa or soft tissue is seen in this section.</div><div>The sinus mucosal tissue shows lymphocytic and </div><div>eosinophilic infiltration.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">Eosinophil count per high power field:</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190103T121100Z</created>
    <updated>20230525T083542Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>___ vocal cord, endolaryngeal microsurgery ---  epithelial cyst.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows epithelial-type cyst and an intact surface squamous epithelium. The cyst is lined by flattened epithelium. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Actinomycosis</title>
    <created>20190329T080643Z</created>
    <updated>20240713T030325Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Actinomycosis characterized by club-shaped filamentous organisms in a radiating pattern is seen</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="color:rgb(33, 33, 33);">Actinomyces are a part of the normal flora of the cervicofacial region, gastrointestinal tract, and urogenital tract</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADCC</title>
    <created>20170117T010257Z</created>
    <updated>20230705T074859Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows salivary gland tissue with an infiltrative tumor composed of neoplastic cells arranged in tubular and cribriform patterns, with perineural invasion. The tumor cells show angular cells mixed with oval cells. The stroma is hyalinized and contains</div><div>base membrane material. The surgical margin is involved. Immunohistochemical stains show that p63, p40 and S-100 reveals variable staining in tumor cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>-- Tumor type: adenoid cystic carcinoma</div><div>Solid component: </div><div>-- Tumor size: </div><div>-- Tumor location: </div><div>-- Tumor extension:</div><div>Tumor extension: The tumor is mainly confined within</div><div>   salivary gland parenchyma. Focal infiltrate into</div><div>   surrounding soft tissue is seen microscopically.</div><div>   Extraparenchymal extension: absent</div><div>   NOTE: Extraparenchymal extension is clinical or</div><div>   macroscopic evidence of invasion of soft tissues.</div><div>   Microscopic evidence alone does not constitute</div><div>   extraparenchymal extension for classification purposes.</div><div><br/></div><div>-- Tumor grade: I (tubular and cribriform areas without solid area)</div><div>High-grade transformation: present/absent</div><div>-- Tumor necrosis: </div><div>-- Perineural invasion: </div><div>-- Vascular invasion: </div><div>-- Regional lymph node status: </div><div>Size of Largest Metastatic Deposit (centimeters): ____ cm Extranodal Extension (ENE) ___ Not identified ___ Present + Distance from lymph node capsule (millimeters): _____ mm +___ ENEma (>2 mm) +___ ENEmi (≤2 mm)</div><div>-- Surgical margin: </div><div>-- Immunohistochemical stains:</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div> </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Allergic fungal sinusitis</title>
    <created>20260114T024045Z</created>
    <updated>20260122T082023Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Allergic fungal sinusitis.</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The section shows eosinophilic mucin with necrotic</div><div>eosinophils, inflammatory cells, and crystals</div><div>Some fungal elements are identified by PAS.c</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Allergic fungal sinusitis.</title>
    <created>20190711T015505Z</created>
    <updated>20190711T015846Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The sinus mucosal tissues show glandular proliferation,</div><div>marked stromal edema, lymphocytic and abundant eosinophilic</div><div>infiltration. Some mucoid and eosinophilic</div><div>exudate is noted, admixed with fungal elements, which are</div><div>also highlighted by PAS. No evidence of malignancy is noted.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Ameloblastoma, unicystic, mural involvement</title>
    <created>20200117T015112Z</created>
    <updated>20260402T063840Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show cystic spaces lined by odontogenic</div><div>epithelium with barely evidence of ameloblastic change,</div><div>however, typical ameloblastic epithelial nests or sheets can</div><div>be identified in the cystic fibrous walls that with typical</div><div>features of palisading basal cells with reverse polarity and</div><div>subnuclear vacuoles. Foci of palisading with thicken</div><div>basement membrane still can be identified. The X-ray images</div><div>further strengthen the diagnosis of unicystic ameloblastoma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Basal cell adenoma (salivary gland)</title>
    <created>20161230T024228Z</created>
    <updated>20161230T024250Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show salivary gland tissue and one encapsulated tumor featuring proliferative basaloid cell in trabecular and tubular pattern with focal palisading. There is no evidence of invasion.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Branchial cleft cyst</title>
    <created>20161103T061406Z</created>
    <updated>20240115T134743Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Branchial cleft cyst</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a cystic lesion lined by respiratory squamous epithelium. Lymphoid stroma with  hyperplasia is noted in the cystic wall. Lobules of salivary gland acini are focally  seen. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>C/W inflamed cyst.</title>
    <created>20180228T082044Z</created>
    <updated>20250910T061122Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Consistent with inflammatory odontogenic cyst.</div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows diffuse infiltrate of neutrophils, and lymphoplasmacytic cells. Focal lining of stratified squamous epithelium is seen. No malignancy is observed.    </div><div style="padding-left:40px;">    </div><div>Fragmented bony spicules are also seen. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>consistent with inflammatory odontogenic cyst.</div><div>    </div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a cystic lesion focally lined by stratified squamous epithelium. There is infiltrate of neutrophils, and lymphoplasmacytic cells. No malignancy is oberved.                 </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>C/W sialolithiasis</title>
