      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>necrotizing sialometaplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Nonkeratinizing carcinoma (NPC), undifferentiated subtype, nasopharynx, biopsy</title>
    <created>20161130T094040Z</created>
    <updated>20250829T020821Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Nonkeratinizing nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC).</div><div>Nasopharyngeal carcinoma, nonkeratinizing, undifferentiated type</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows sheets of neoplastic cells in syncytial growth pattern, accompanied by intermingled lymphocytes. The tumor cells are characterized by large, vesicular nuclei with distinct nucleoli and lightly eosinophilic cytoplasm with focal spindling.</div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the tumor cells are positive for p40 and AE1/AE3. EBER is positive within a few individual cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>Histological type: Nonkeratinizing nasopharyngeal carcinoma, undifferentiated subtype.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>NSD</title>
    <created>20180503T065554Z</created>
    <updated>20181205T053835Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>clinically nasal septal deviation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Strip of hyaline cartilage is consistent with septal cartilage.<br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>odontogenic keratocyst</title>
    <created>20190506T074258Z</created>
    <updated>20260422T045911Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Odontogenic keratocyst.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows fibrous wall lined by epithelial cells</div><div>featuring basal cel palisading with reversal of nuclear</div><div>polarity, and corrugated parakeratin surface.</div><div>Focal infiltrate of acute and chronic inflammatory cells is</div><div>seen.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Odontoma (compound)</title>
    <created>20170703T062658Z</created>
    <updated>20220302T072041Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Odontoma (compound).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows dentin and enamel matrix which have architeture similar to normal tooth.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Oroantral fistula.</title>
    <created>20200511T082706Z</created>
    <updated>20200511T082850Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Consistent with oroantral fistula.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows squamous mucosal tissue with a fistulous tract</div><div>lined by stratified squamous and respiratory-type</div><div>epithelium. The surrounding fibrous connective tissue</div><div>exhibits infiltrate of lymphoplasmacytic cells as well as</div><div>occasional neutrophils.</div><div>No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>oropharynx SCC, HPV-associated</title>
    <created>20240913T083451Z</created>
    <updated>20240913T083521Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma, HPV-associated</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows neoplastic cells with basaloid feature in papillary growth. </div><div><br/></div><div>p40: positive.</div><div>P16: overexpression. </div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Oropharynx SCC, HPV-independent</title>
    <created>20250213T043923Z</created>
    <updated>20250213T044308Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Left upper tonsillar fossa, biopsy --- Squamous cell carcinoma, HPV-independent.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows irregularly proliferative nests of neoplastic</div><div>squamous cells revealing distinct nuclear pleomorphism and</div><div>mitotic activity with stromal invasion.    </div><div>    </div><div>Ancillary studies: </div><div>p40: positive.</div><div>P16: no overexpression. </div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Orthokeratinized odontogenic cyst</title>
    <created>20260422T050117Z</created>
    <updated>20260422T050220Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Orthokeratinized odontogenic cyst</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The section shows noninflamed fibrous cyst wall lined by thin uniform stratified squamous epithelium with thick luminal lamellated keratin.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20211026T014757Z</created>
    <updated>20241111T081621Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>osteonecrosis with Actinomycotic infestation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows Actinomycosis with associated neutrophilic infiltrate involving necrotic bone.</div><div>PAS stain demonstrates the filamentous organisms in a radiating pattern. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Otic polyp</title>
    <created>20180716T064720Z</created>
    <updated>20180716T064931Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Otic polyp</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section reveals a polypoid fragment of tissue, showing</div><div>surface metaplastic squamous epithelium , which surrounds</div><div>fibrosis and inflammation which is composed of abundant</div><div>plasma cells with a rich vascular tissue.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180426T043916Z</created>
    <updated>20231227T071226Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Papillary squamous cell carcinoma, p16-positive.<br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows neoplastic squamous cells with cellular atypia and increased mitotic activity, arranged in papillary</div><div>pattern with focal stromal invasion. A maturation trend with minimal surface parakeratin is focally seen.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical study:</div><div>P16: overexpression in tumor cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>Human papillomavirus (HPV)-mediated squamous cell carcinoma should be considered.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190307T101002Z</created>
    <updated>20260129T080805Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="padding-left:40px;">Parathyroid adenoma</div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div style="padding-left:40px;">Microscopic description:</div><div style="padding-left:40px;">Sections show a demarcated nodule that is predominantly</div><div style="padding-left:40px;">comprised of chief cells. Rim of normal parathyroid is</div><div style="padding-left:40px;">seen separated by a capsule.</div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div style="padding-left:40px;">By immunohistochemistry, the lesional cells are positive for</div><div style="padding-left:40px;">synaptophysin but not TTF-1, confirming the diagnosis.</div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Periapical cyst (Radicular cyst)</title>
    <created>20170314T062632Z</created>
    <updated>20250919T092832Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Consistent with periapical cyst (Radicular cyst).</span></div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cystic lesion focally lined by stratified squamous epithelium accompanied by diffuse infiltrate of neutrophils and lymphoplasmacytic cells. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Fragmented bony spicules are also seen. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Pseudocyst, ear</title>
    <created>20170320T072302Z</created>
    <updated>20260430T055550Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">Pseudocyst.</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cartilage separated by a cystic cavity lined by granulation tissue and fibrous connective tissue. No malignancy is observed.    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>salivary gland neoplasm, not further specified (with myoepithelial differentiation)</title>
    <created>20200930T011646Z</created>
    <updated>20230705T074853Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><h3>salivary gland neoplasm, not further specified.</h3><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows squamous mucosal tissue with a separate tumor</div><div>fragment composed of both ductal and myoepithelial cells</div><div>which are highlighted by CK7, S100, SMMHC, p63, and</div><div>The Ki-67 index is low. No mucus cell is demonstrated by mucicarmine stain.</div><div><br/></div><div>The immunohistochemical profile suggests salivary gland neoplasm with myoepithelial differentiation, including pleomorphic adenoma, myoepithelial neoplasm, adenoid cystic carcinoma, epi-myoepithelial carcinoma, and polymorphous low-grade adenocarcinoma. There is substantial overlap in the immunohistochemical profile among these tumors.</div><div>Fragment contains entirely of lesional cells without surrounding tissue to evaluate for invasion.</div><div>Conservative but complete excision is recommended for a definite diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><h3>salivary gland neoplasm, not further specified.</h3><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows salivary lobules with tumor fragments composed of both ductal and myoepithelial cells, which are highlighted by CK7, S100 and p63, in a myxoid background.</div><div><br/></div><div>The immunohistochemical profile suggests salivary gland neoplasm with ductal and myoepithelial differentiation. Based on the morphology,</div><div>pleomorphic adenoma should be considered.</div><div><br/></div><div>However, fragment contains few surrounding tissue to evaluate for invasion. Conservative but complete excision is recommended for a definite diagnosis.</div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190502T053930Z</created>
    <updated>20250103T062329Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sinonasal inflammatory polyp</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Polypoid mass is seen with intact covering</div><div>respiratory epithelium and underlying stroma characterized</div><div>by edema, inflammatory infiltrate, and increased vascularity</div><div>with abscence of mucoserous glands.    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Sinonasal papilloma, oncocytic</title>
    <created>20251021T025650Z</created>
    <updated>20251021T025659Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Sinonasal papilloma, oncocytic</div><div>Microscopic description:</div><ol><li><div>The section shows mixed exophytic and endophytic growth pattern, composed of oncocytic cuboidal to columnar cells and intraepithelial microcysts with mucin and neutrophilic microabscesses. By immunohistochemistry, p40 highlights the basal cells. No malignant transformation is seen.</div></li></ol></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Solid cell nest, thyroid</title>
    <created>20161128T091039Z</created>
    <updated>20161201T151540Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Focal solid cell nest is identified which is      
positive for p63 and CEA immunostains.
</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Spindle cell squamous carcinoma.</title>
    <created>20220512T095852Z</created>
    <updated>20240920T092244Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>spindle cell squamous carcinoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows sheets of tumor cells which are spindle to epithelioid with marked cellular atypism and increased mitotic activity in a myxoid stroma.</div><div>Adjacent squamoid tumor cells with keratinization are also seen. Immunohistochemically, the sarcomatoid area is focally positive for AE1/AE3, and diffusely positive for p63, consistent with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180806T022057Z</created>
    <updated>20180806T022359Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Squamous cell carcinoma<br/></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows nests neoplastic cells with cellular atypia and stromal invasion. Dysplasia of the overlying squamous epithelium is seen. Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for AE1/AE3 and p40, but not P16.</div><div><br/></div><div>Histologic Type:</div><div>Histologic Grade: ___ G1: Well differentiated</div><div>___ G2: Moderately differentiated</div><div>___ G3: Poorly differentiated</div><div>Margins:</div><div>___ Cannot be assessed</div><div>___ Uninvolved by invasive tumor</div><div>Distance from closest margin: ____ mm</div><div>___ Involved by invasive tumor</div><div>___ Uninvolved by high-grade dysplasia/in situ disease</div><div>Distance from closest margin: ____ mm</div><div>___ Involved by high-grade dysplasia/in situ disease</div><div>Lymphovascular Invasion</div><div>___ Not identified</div><div>___ Present</div><div>Perineural Invasion (Note F)</div><div>___ Not identified</div><div>___ Present</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Squamous cell carcinoma, p16-positive oropharynx</title>
    <created>20180426T044707Z</created>
    <updated>20250213T044004Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>squamous cell carcinoma, p16-positive.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows invasive nests of non-keratinizing, neoplastic</div><div>squamous cells with high N:C ratio and increased mitotic</div><div>activity.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical study:</div><div>P16: overexpression in tumor cells. Human papillomavirus</div><div>(HPV)-mediated squamous cell carcinoma should be considered.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis (de Quervain thyroiditis) (thyroid)</title>
    <created>20170117T011823Z</created>
    <updated>20170117T011852Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Sections show focally destroyed thyroid follicles by marked inflammatory infiltrate which is composed of lymphocytes, plasma cells, neutrophils, and epithelioid histiocytes. Granulomas containing multinucleated giant cells are seen both within the</div><div>thyroid follicles and interfollicular regions. There is also interfollicular fibrosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, IgG highlights scattered plasma cells without increased IgG4/IgG ratio as determined by immunostains, excluding IgG4 related disease. There are no mycobacterial microorganisms as demonstrated by acid fast, and </div><div>Auramine-Rhodamine stains. No fungus is demonstrated by GMS and PAS. </div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, the overall features are compatible with subacute granulomatous thyroiditis (de Quervain thyroiditis). Four lymph nodes are identified with preserved </div><div>nodal architecture. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20170523T021617Z</created>
    <updated>20170523T021633Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px;">The covering respiratory epithelium shows squamous metaplasia and appears to be intact </span><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">and lacks any cellular atypia. The underlying lymphoid stroma shows proliferation of lymphoid tissue with germinal center formation. No evidence of tumor cell infiltration is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.</span></span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20221031T061917Z</created>
    <updated>20221031T062433Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-url>https://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/thyroidthyroglossal.html</source-url>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><h3 style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: bold; font-size: 18px; line-height: 24px; font-family: Arial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><span style="border: 0px; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: bold; font-size: 18px; line-height: 24px; font-family: Arial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;">Thyroglossal duct cyst.</span></h3><div><span style="border: 0px; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: bold; font-size: 18px; line-height: 24px; font-family: Arial; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;"><br/></span></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cystic lesion lined by respiratory-type epithelium, with thyroid follicles in the cystic wall.</div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Thyroid</title>
    <created>20140715T023846Z</created>
    <updated>20231227T071238Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div><br/></div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div>Sections of the cystic mass of the right lobe of thyroid reveal a cystic wall with fibrosis and inflammatory exudates. No papillary tumor is left in the sections. The frozen section (2015-04-2161) is reviewed, and it shows a small focus of papillary carcinoma. The following histologic details are defined with incorporation of the findings of the frozen section.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><ul><li><div>Consistent with Graves disease</div></li><ul><li><div>Sections show hyperplastic follicles with papillary infolding, lined by cuboidal epithelium with uniform nuclei and prominent scalloping of the colloid. The stroma contains aggregates of lymphoid tissue with focal germinal center formation. The clinical and pathologic features are consistent with Graves disease. No malignancy is observed.</div></li><li><div>Anti-Tg _ IU/mL (↑), Anti-TPO _.1 IU/mL (↑), TSH _ uIU/mL (↓), T3 _ ng/dl (↑), T4 _ ug/dl (nl), Thyroglobulin _ ng/mL (nl)</div></li></ul><li><div>Diffuse hyperplasia, parathyroid gland</div></li><ul><li><div>Sections reveal parathyroid tissues with hyperplastic change. There are secondary changes including calcifications, cholesterol clefts formation and presence of hemosiderin-laden macrophages. No evidence of malignancy is discerned.</div></li></ul></ul><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Thyroid ITCs</title>
    <created>20240812T021108Z</created>
    <updated>20240812T021125Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>NOTE:</div><div>Isolated tumor cells (ITCs) were identified in one lymph</div><div>node. However, there is no definitive guideline on whether</div><div>ITCs should be classified as pN0(i+), so in this case,</div><div>classification as pN1a is applied. Based on a few studies,</div><div>like micrometastasis, ITCs do not appear to carry a higher</div><div>risk of locoregional recurrence compared to node-negative</div><div>patients.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Thyroid, follicular adenoma</title>
    <created>20161205T070838Z</created>
    <updated>20241127T031431Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>follicular adenoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The histologic findings reveal a thinly encapsulated tumor, which architecturally and cytologically is different from the surrounding compressed gland. It is composed of crowded follicles with diminished colloid. No vascular or capsular invasion as to</div><div>suggest malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div>Sections show a thinly encapsulated tumor composed predominantly of crowded follicles lined by uniform cuboid cells with diminished colloid, arranged in microfollicular, trabecular and organoid patterns. No vascular or capsular invasion as to suggest malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Thyroid, psammoma bodies in lymph nodes</title>
    <created>20161223T045841Z</created>
    <updated>20161223T045857Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Although a few psammoma bodies are identified in two lymph nodes, cytokeratin AE1/AE3 immunostaining is negative,   excluding metastatic carcinoma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Tonsilar-type cyst. larynx</title>
    <created>20220103T043301Z</created>
    <updated>20230919T043126Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Tonsilar-type cyst.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows submucosal epithelial cyst with lymphoid follicles and germinal centers in the cyst wall and an intact surface squamous epithelium.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Tonsillar cyst</title>
    <created>20161203T023246Z</created>
    <updated>20240701T025823Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>tonsillar cyst.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cystic lesion covered by squamous epithelium with lymphoid tissue in  </div><div>wall. No fungus is demonstrated by GMS or PAS.  </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>torus mandibularis</title>
